
[1]silly

   SIL'LY, a. [Heb. This may be radically the same word, with a prefix.
   Class Sl. No. 26]

   1. Weak in intellect; foolish; witless; destitute of ordinary strength
   of mind; simple; as a silly man; a silly child.

   2. Proceeding from want of understanding or common judgment;
   characterized by weakness of folly; unwise; as silly thoughts; silly
   actions; a silly scheme; writings stupid or silly.

   3. Weak; helpless. After long storms- With which my silly bark was
   toss'd
